---
/**
 * Tutorial 02 -- Design Tokens
 *
 * Tokens are named design values (colors, spacing, radii, etc.) that
 * vary across "axes" -- dimensions like theme, density, contrast, or
 * motion preference. czap compiles tokens to CSS custom properties,
 * so they participate in the cascade naturally.
 *
 * In this tutorial you will:
 *   1. See how Token.make() creates a content-addressed token definition
 *   2. Understand axes and how they control token resolution
 *   3. Learn about the @token CSS block (compiled by @czap/vite)
 *   4. See tokens rendered as CSS custom properties in a live demo
 */

import Base from '../layouts/Base.astro';
import { gapSm, gapMd, gapLg } from '../tokens/spacing.tokens.js';
---

<Base title="Design Tokens">

  <!-- ============================================================
       STEP 1: What is a Token?
       ============================================================

       A token is a named design value with variants along axes.
       Unlike simple CSS custom properties, tokens are:

         - Content-addressed (change the definition, hash changes)
         - Multi-axis (one token can vary by theme AND density)
         - Resolvable anywhere (server, client, build time, tests)
         - Compilable to multiple targets (CSS, GLSL, WGSL, ARIA)

       The simplest token has one axis with two variants.
  -->

  <h1>02 -- Design Tokens</h1>

  <p>
    A <strong>token</strong> is a named design value that varies across
    one or more axes. An axis is any dimension of variation: theme,
    density, contrast, motion preference, or even a custom axis you define.
  </p>

  <div class="note">
    <strong>Key idea:</strong> Tokens are not just CSS variables. They're
    structured data that czap compiles <em>into</em> CSS variables (among
    other targets). The token definition is the source of truth; the CSS
    custom property is a compiled output.
  </div>

  <!-- ============================================================
       STEP 2: Defining Tokens

       Here's the TypeScript definition from spacing.tokens.ts.
       Each token has:
         - name:     CSS property name (becomes --gap-sm, etc.)
         - category: semantic grouping (spacing, color, typography...)
         - axes:     which dimensions this token varies along
         - values:   a map of axis values to design values
         - fallback: default when no axis matches
  -->

  <h2>Defining Tokens</h2>

  <pre><code>import {'{'} Token {'}'} from '@czap/core';

export const gapSm = Token.make({'{'}&br;
  name: 'gap-sm',
  category: 'spacing',
  axes: ['density'] as const,
  values: {'{'}&br;
    default: '0.5rem',   // Standard spacing
    compact: '0.25rem',  // Tighter for dense layouts
  {'}'},
  fallback: '0.5rem',
{'}'});

export const gapMd = Token.make({'{'}&br;
  name: 'gap-md',
  category: 'spacing',
  axes: ['density'] as const,
  values: {'{'}&br;
    default: '1rem',
    compact: '0.5rem',
  {'}'},
  fallback: '1rem',
{'}'});

export const gapLg = Token.make({'{'}&br;
  name: 'gap-lg',
  category: 'spacing',
  axes: ['density'] as const,
  values: {'{'}&br;
    default: '2rem',
    compact: '1rem',
  {'}'},
  fallback: '2rem',
{'}'});</code></pre>

  <!-- ============================================================
       STEP 3: How Tokens Become CSS

       The @czap/vite plugin transforms @token CSS blocks at build
       time. When you write:

         @token {
           gap: var(--gap-md);
         }

       The Vite plugin resolves --gap-md against the token registry,
       applies the current axis values, and emits the resolved CSS
       custom property.

       At runtime, the tokens land as standard CSS custom properties
       on the element or :root. You use them like any other custom
       property: var(--gap-md).
  -->

  <h2>Tokens as CSS Custom Properties</h2>

  <p>
    czap compiles each token to a CSS custom property. The property name
    is derived from the token's <code>name</code> field, prefixed with
    <code>--</code>:
  </p>

  <pre><code>/* After compilation, your CSS can reference tokens directly: */
.card {'{'}&br;
  padding: var(--gap-md);     /* 1rem in default density    */
  gap: var(--gap-sm);         /* 0.5rem in default density  */
  margin-bottom: var(--gap-lg); /* 2rem in default density  */
{'}'}

/* The @token CSS block (processed by @czap/vite) declares which
   tokens a component uses. This enables tree-shaking and
   ahead-of-time resolution: */

@token {'{'}&br;
  --gap-sm: spacing;
  --gap-md: spacing;
  --gap-lg: spacing;
{'}'}</code></pre>

  <div class="note">
    <strong>Why @token blocks?</strong> They serve as explicit declarations
    of token dependencies. The Vite plugin uses them to: (1) resolve tokens
    at build time, (2) tree-shake unused tokens, and (3) generate
    optimized CSS with only the tokens a component actually uses.
  </div>

  <!-- ============================================================
       STEP 4: Live Demo

       This demo shows the three spacing tokens applied to a set of
       cards. The CSS custom properties are set inline here for
       demonstration, but in a real app the @czap/vite plugin would
       inject them automatically from your token definitions.

       Try inspecting the elements in DevTools -- you'll see the
       --gap-sm, --gap-md, --gap-lg custom properties.
  -->

  <h2>Live Demo</h2>

  <p>
    The cards below use the spacing tokens as CSS custom properties.
    Inspect them in DevTools to see <code>--gap-sm</code>,
    <code>--gap-md</code>, and <code>--gap-lg</code> in action.
  </p>

  <!-- We set the token values as inline custom properties here for
       the tutorial. In production, the @czap/vite plugin resolves
       them from your token definitions at build time. -->
  <div
    class="token-demo"
    style={`--gap-sm: ${gapSm.fallback}; --gap-md: ${gapMd.fallback}; --gap-lg: ${gapLg.fallback};`}
  >
    <div class="token-card">
      <h3>--gap-sm</h3>
      <p>Padding uses <code>var(--gap-sm)</code></p>
      <div class="swatch" style="padding: var(--gap-sm); background: #eef2ff;">
        {String(gapSm.fallback)} (default density)
      </div>
    </div>

    <div class="token-card">
      <h3>--gap-md</h3>
      <p>Padding uses <code>var(--gap-md)</code></p>
      <div class="swatch" style="padding: var(--gap-md); background: #eef2ff;">
        {String(gapMd.fallback)} (default density)
      </div>
    </div>

    <div class="token-card">
      <h3>--gap-lg</h3>
      <p>Padding uses <code>var(--gap-lg)</code></p>
      <div class="swatch" style="padding: var(--gap-lg); background: #eef2ff;">
        {String(gapLg.fallback)} (default density)
      </div>
    </div>
  </div>

  <!-- ============================================================
       STEP 5: Content Addressing

       Every token gets a unique content address (FNV-1a hash) based
       on its name, category, axes, and values. If you change any
       part of the definition, the hash changes, which means:

         - CDN caches invalidate automatically
         - Hot module replacement knows exactly what changed
         - Diffing tools can detect token drift between branches
  -->

  <h2>Content Addressing</h2>

  <p>
    Each token has a content address -- an FNV-1a hash of its definition.
    Here are the IDs for our spacing tokens:
  </p>

  <ul>
    <li><code>gap-sm</code>: <code>{gapSm.id}</code></li>
    <li><code>gap-md</code>: <code>{gapMd.id}</code></li>
    <li><code>gap-lg</code>: <code>{gapLg.id}</code></li>
  </ul>

  <p>
    Change a value and the hash changes. This makes cache invalidation
    automatic -- no version bumps, no manual purging.
  </p>

  <!-- ============================================================
       STEP 6: Multi-Axis Tokens

       Tokens can vary along multiple axes simultaneously. A color
       token might vary by both theme (light/dark) and contrast
       (normal/high). The resolution algorithm sorts axes
       alphabetically and builds a compound lookup key.
  -->

  <h2>Multi-Axis Tokens</h2>

  <pre><code>// A token that varies by BOTH theme and contrast:
const textColor = Token.make({'{'}&br;
  name: 'text-primary',
  category: 'color',
  axes: ['theme', 'contrast'] as const,
  values: {'{'}&br;
    'light:normal': '#1a1a2e',
    'light:high':   '#000000',
    'dark:normal':  '#e0e0ff',
    'dark:high':    '#ffffff',
  {'}'},
  fallback: '#1a1a2e',
{'}'});</code></pre>

  <p>
    The axes are sorted alphabetically and joined with <code>:</code> to
    form compound lookup keys. This means <code>contrast:normal</code> +
    <code>theme:light</code> resolves to the key <code>"light:normal"</code>.
  </p>

  <!-- ============================================================
       STEP 7: What's Next
  -->

  <h2>What You Learned</h2>

  <ul>
    <li><code>Token.make()</code> creates a content-addressed token definition.</li>
    <li>Tokens vary across axes (theme, density, contrast, etc.).</li>
    <li>czap compiles tokens to CSS custom properties via <code>@token</code> blocks.</li>
    <li>Content addressing means automatic cache invalidation on change.</li>
    <li>Multi-axis tokens use sorted, colon-joined compound keys.</li>
  </ul>

  <p>
    <strong>Next:</strong> <a href="/03-themes">03 -- Theme Switching</a> --
    group tokens into coherent themes with light/dark variants.
  </p>

</Base>

<style>
  .token-demo {
    display: flex;
    gap: var(--gap-md, 1rem);
    flex-wrap: wrap;
    margin-bottom: 2rem;
  }

  .token-card {
    flex: 1;
    min-width: 180px;
    background: #fff;
    border: 1px solid #e2e8f0;
    border-radius: 8px;
    padding: 1.25rem;
  }

  .token-card h3 {
    color: #4f46e5;
    font-family: 'SF Mono', 'Fira Code', monospace;
    font-size: 1rem;
    margin-bottom: 0.5rem;
  }

  .swatch {
    border-radius: 4px;
    font-size: 0.875rem;
    font-family: 'SF Mono', 'Fira Code', monospace;
    color: #4f46e5;
    margin-top: 0.75rem;
  }
</style>
